<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">
This species was recorded from India by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hancock, DL" journalOrPublisher="Steenstrupia" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" pagination="1 - 17" refId="B9" refString="Hancock, DL, McGuire, DJ, 2002. New species and records of non-dacine fruit flies (Insecta: Diptera: Tephritidae) from South and South-east Asia. Steenstrupia 27 (1): 1 - 17" title="New species and records of non-dacine fruit flies (Insecta: Diptera: Tephritidae) from South and South-east Asia." volume="27" year="2002">Hancock and McGuire (2002)</bibRefCitation>
, based on two males and two females from Gulmarg, Kashmir. However, given the complexity of this group, additional material is required for confirmation. Elsewhere, it is widespread from Western Europe to Central Asia, including Afghanistan (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00305316.2005.10417450" author="Agarwal, ML" journalOrPublisher="Oriental Insects" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" pagination="371 - 433" refId="B2" refString="Agarwal, ML, Sueyoshi, M, 2005. Catalogue of Indian fruit flies (Diptera: Tephritidae). Oriental Insects 39: 371 - 433, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00305316.2005.10417450" title="Catalogue of Indian fruit flies (Diptera: Tephritidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00305316.2005.10417450" volume="39" year="2005">Agarwal and Sueyoshi 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
